From b5ddaa331188af4fa0fec70bcf879854d7be58d6 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Wed, 8 Jul 2026 13:01:05 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Evaluate @supports feature queries instead of assuming
 support

An @supports rule was applied whenever its condition parsed as a valid
<supports-condition>, treating every well-formed feature query as supported.
That wrongly applied rules gated on unsupported queries: an invalid value
(color: rainbow), an unknown property (unknown: green), or a <general-enclosed>
block, all of which must evaluate to false (WPT css-conditional css-supports-005,
009, 010, 020, 030).

Replace the optimistic gate with a real evaluation. SupportsConditionSyntax now
returns a tri-state (Invalid/False/True): a feature query is resolved through a
support oracle, a <general-enclosed> group evaluates to false (so not (@page) is
true), and and/or/not fold the results per the grammar. CssStyleEngine's oracle
(IsFeatureQuerySupported) accepts a query only when the property is recognised and
the value is valid for it, including a real <color> check that rejects rainbow.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
Claude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_01TaHAU6QPbKQc9hj1xBBdRR
